1 (2) “Account” means the Catastrophic Event Account.
2 (3) “FUND” MEANS THE STATE DISASTER RECOVERY FUND
3 ESTABLISHED UNDER § 14–110.5 OF THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE.
4 (b) Subject to the provisions of this section, the Account is established to enable
5 the State or a local government to respond without undue delay to a natural disaster or
6 other catastrophic situation, or federal employee financial hardship from a full or partial
7 federal government shutdown due to a lapse in federal appropriations that cannot be taken
8 care of within the resources of existing appropriations.
9 (c) The Governor may provide an appropriation in the budget bill to the Account.
10 (d) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, after a [15–day] 5–DAY
11 review and comment period by the Legislative Policy Committee, the Governor may
12 transfer funds by budget amendment from the Account to:
13 (I) the expenditure accounts of the appropriate unit of State
14 government or unit of local government; OR
15 (II) SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (E)(2)(II) OF THIS SECTION, THE
16 STATE DISASTER RECOVERY FUND.
17 (2) If the federal government is in a full or partial shutdown due to a lapse
18 in appropriations, after a 2–day review and comment period by the Legislative Policy
19 Committee, the Governor may transfer funds by budget amendment from the Account to
20 the Federal Government Shutdown Employee Assistance Loan Fund established under §
21 7–327 of this subtitle.
22 (e) Funds appropriated to the Catastrophic Event Account:
23 (1) may not be used to offset operating deficiencies in regular programs of
24 State government; but
25 (2) (I) may be expended to assist a unit of State government or unit of
26 local government in funding costs in connection with a natural disaster, a catastrophic
27 situation, or a full or partial federal government shutdown due to a lapse in appropriations;
28 AND
29 (II) MAY BE TRANSFERRED TO THE STATE DISASTER
30 RECOVERY FUND IF:
31 1. THE BALANCE OF THE FUND HAS BEEN DEPLETED
32 DUE TO USE OR TRANSFER; OR

4 HOUSE BILL 865
1 2. THE ESTIMATED COSTS FOR PROVIDING ADEQUATE
2 DISASTER RELIEF FOR A NATURAL DISASTER OR CATASTROPHIC SITUATION ARE IN
3 EXCESS OF THE FUND’S BALANCE.
4 (f) (1) The Account is a continuing, nonlapsing fund which is not subject to §
5 7–302 of this subtitle.
6 (2) The Treasurer shall separately hold, and the Comptroller shall account
7 for, the Account.
8 (3) The Account shall be invested and reinvested in the same manner as
9 other State funds.
10 (4) Any investment earnings shall be subject to § 7–311(d) of this subtitle.
11 (g) Money appropriated to the Account does not revert to the Revenue
12 Stabilization Account.
13 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
14 1, 2025.
